I'm sorry to hear that the changes did not fix the issue. Without seeing the full code and seeing what's happening in the browser's console, it's difficult to determine what the issue might be. However, here are a few more suggestions you can try:

1. Make sure that the `Dropzone` library is being loaded correctly. You can check the browser's console for any errors related to the `Dropzone` library.

2. Add `autoProcessQueue: false` to the `Dropzone` initialization script. This will prevent `Dropzone` from automatically uploading the files when they are added.

3. Manually trigger the form submission when the translate button is clicked. This will allow the target language list and file to be sent to the backend. Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

```
<form id="my-form" action="/localization/multi-local-from-file" method="post" enctype="multipart/form-data">
  ...
  <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" id="translate-btn">Translate</button>
  ...
</form>

<script type="text/javascript">
  $("#my-dropzone").dropzone({
    url: "/localization/multi-local-from-file",
    addRemoveLinks: true,
    paramName: "data",
    maxFiles: 1,
    maxFilesize: 10,
    acceptedFiles: ".arb",
    autoProcessQueue: false,
    init: function() {
      this.on("success", function(file, response) {
        // On successful translation, enable the download button and change the download link
        $("#download-multiple").prop("href", URL.createObjectURL(response));
        $("#download-multiple").prop("disabled", false);
      });
    }
  });

  $("#translate-btn").on("click", function() {
    // Manually process the queue and submit the form
    $("#my-dropzone").get(0).processQueue();
    $("#my-form").submit();
  });
</script>
```

This code adds a button element that triggers the form submission when clicked. The `autoProcessQueue: false` option is added to the `Dropzone` initialization script to prevent the files from being immediately uploaded.

