If you want to display only the last post from the database, you can change the `fetchData` function in your `FutureMK` component to fetch only the last document from the Firestore collection.

First, you'll need to modify the query to sort the documents based on the timestamp or any other unique attribute that defines the order. Then, you should limit the results to 1, so you only get the last post.

Here's the updated `FutureMK` component with a modified `fetchData` function that fetches only the last post:

```javascript
//... other imports ...
import 'firebase/compat/firestore';

export default function FutureMK() {
  const navigation = useNavigation();
  const [futureMKData, setFutureMKData] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchData = async () => {
      try {
        const futureMKRef = firebase
          .firestore()
          .collection('FutureMK')
          .orderBy('time', 'desc')
          .limit(1);

        const snapshot = await futureMKRef.get();
        const data = snapshot.docs.map((doc) => ({ id: doc.id, ...doc.data() }));
        const storage = firebase.storage();
        const updatedData = await Promise.all(
          data.map(async (mkData) => {
            const imagePath = mkData.image;
            const imageRef = storage.ref().child(imagePath);
            const url = await imageRef.getDownloadURL();
            return { ...mkData, image: url };
          })
        );
        setFutureMKData(updatedData);
      } catch (error) {
        console.log('Error:', error);
      }
    };

    fetchData();
  }, []);

  // ... rest of the component
}
```

In this updated version, we added `.orderBy('time', 'desc')` to sort the documents in descending order based on the 'time' field. We also added `.limit(1)` to the query to fetch only the last document.

Please note that you should replace `'time'` with the correct field name used in your Firestore collection for sorting the documents.

To achieve this, you can create a new prop for your `FutureMK` component called `limit`, which will be used to control the number of posts to fetch for each screen. By default, it will fetch all posts, but when used on the `Home` screen, you can pass `2` as the `limit` prop to fetch only the last two posts.

Here's the updated `FutureMK` component with the `limit` prop:

